- Use `dotnet new mvc -n LoggingApp` to create a new ASP.NET Core MVC project.
- Update `Program.cs` to configure logging with:
  ```csharp
  builder.Services.AddLogging(builder =>
  {
      builder.ClearProviders();
      builder.AddConsole();
      builder.AddDebug();
  });
  ```
- Use `ILogger<T>` for logging in your controllers and services.
- Configure log levels in `appsettings.json`:
  ```json
  "Logging": {
    "LogLevel": {
      "Default": "Information",
      "Microsoft.AspNetCore": "Warning"
    }
  }
  ```
- For high-performance logging, consider using `Serilog` or `NLog` by installing their NuGet packages and configuring them in `Program.cs`.
- Use structured logging to improve log readability and searchability.
- Implement custom log filters for more granular control over what gets logged.

- Use `dotnet new console -n LoggingApp` to create a new .NET console application.
- Install the latest logging provider via NuGet, e.g., `dotnet add package Microsoft.Extensions.Logging.Console`.
- Configure logging in `Program.cs`:
  ```csharp
  var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
  builder.Services.AddLogging(builder => {
      builder.AddConsole();
      builder.AddDebug();
  });
  ```
- Use `ILogger<T>` for logging within your classes, e.g., 
  ```csharp
  public class MyService {
      private readonly ILogger<MyService> _logger;
      public MyService(ILogger<MyService> logger) {
          _logger = logger;
      }
      public void DoWork() {
          _logger.LogInformation("Doing work...");
      }
  }
  ```
- For database logging, consider `Microsoft.Extensions.Logging.EntityFrameworkCore` for Entity Framework Core.
- Key config options in `appsettings.json`:
  ```json
  "Logging": {
    "LogLevel": {
      "Default": "Information",
      "Microsoft.AspNetCore": "Warning"
    },
    "Console": {
      "IncludeScopes": true,
      "LogLevel": {
        "Default": "Debug"
      }
    }
  }
  ```
- Use `ILoggerFactory` for more advanced logging scenarios.
- For production environments, consider using `Serilog` or `NLog` as alternatives to the built-in providers.
